<paragraph blockId="8.[340,983,1241,1265]" box="[340,983,1241,1265]" pageId="8" pageNumber="941">
<heading box="[340,983,1241,1265]" centered="true" fontSize="10" level="2" pageId="8" pageNumber="941" reason="2">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[340,422,1241,1265]" pageId="8" pageNumber="941">Genus</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Deroux" authorityName="Deroux" authorityYear="1975" box="[431,661,1241,1265]" class="Cyrtophoria" family="Dysteriidae" genus="Aegyriana" kingdom="Protozoa" order="Dysteriida" pageId="8" pageNumber="941" phylum="Ciliophora" rank="genus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[431,564,1241,1265]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="941">Aegyriana</emphasis>
Deroux
</taxonomicName>
in Song and 
<bibRefCitation author="Wilbert N" box="[820,983,1241,1265]" pageId="8" pageNumber="941" pagination="23 - 61" refId="ref16780" refString="Song W and Wilbert N. 2002. Faunistic studies on marine ciliates form the Antarctic benthic area, including descriptions of one epizoic form, 6 new species and 2 new genera (Protozoa: Ciliophora). Acta Protozoologica 41: 23 - 61." type="journal article" year="2002">Wilbert, 2002</bibRefCitation>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[138,1185,1301,1422]" pageId="8" pageNumber="941">
In original description, the oral structure was insufficiently and incorrectly interpreted as it is difficult to detect because of its extremely anterior position (
<bibRefCitation author="Deroux G" box="[893,1056,1333,1357]" pageId="8" pageNumber="941" pagination="155 - 182" refId="ref15345" refString="Deroux G. 1970. La serie '' Chlamydonellienne' ' chez les Chlamydodontidae (Holotriches, Cyrtophorina Faure- Fremiet). Protistologica 6: 155 - 182." type="journal article" year="1970">Deroux 1970</bibRefCitation>
; Song and 
<bibRefCitation author="Wilbert N" box="[138,304,1366,1390]" pageId="8" pageNumber="941" pagination="23 - 61" refId="ref16780" refString="Song W and Wilbert N. 2002. Faunistic studies on marine ciliates form the Antarctic benthic area, including descriptions of one epizoic form, 6 new species and 2 new genera (Protozoa: Ciliophora). Acta Protozoologica 41: 23 - 61." type="journal article" year="2002">Wilbert 2002</bibRefCitation>
). With the current population we had the opportunity to make further observations, so that an improved definition can be given here.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="941" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="8.[138,346,1479,1503]" box="[138,346,1479,1503]" pageId="8" pageNumber="941">
<emphasis box="[138,346,1479,1503]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="941">Improved diagnosis</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[138,1185,1528,1681]" pageId="8" pageNumber="941">
Dorsoventrally flattened 
<taxonomicName authorityName="E.Claparede &amp; J.Lachmann" authorityYear="1858" box="[455,587,1528,1552]" class="Cyrtophoria" family="Dysteriidae" kingdom="Protozoa" order="Dysteriida" pageId="8" pageNumber="941" phylum="Ciliophora" rank="family">Dysteriidae</taxonomicName>
with tail-shaped podite, which is positioned subcaudally in a glabrous region within the somatic kineties; oral ciliature in two parts: ca three close-set fragments on right and one kinety on left; left postoral kineties shortened posteriorly and continuous with right ones, leaving no median gap or suture; cytopharyngeal rods prominent.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
